<i>♪ Sing it right ♪</i>

02:27.816 --> 02:30.360
<i>♪ Once or twice ♪</i>

02:30.443 --> 02:32.612
<i>♪ Oh, lordy me ♪</i>

02:32.695 --> 02:35.365
<i>♪ Didn't I shake sugaree? ♪</i>

02:36.157 --> 02:40.537
<i>♪ Everything I got is done and pawned ♪</i>

02:40.620 --> 02:42.455
Yeah.

02:46.751 --> 02:47.752
Ed?

02:55.969 --> 02:57.011
I fucked up.

02:59.430 --> 03:01.349
There's no other way to say it.

03:03.017 --> 03:07.021
And I don't think that I'm gonna wrap it
in a bow and make it better,

03:07.105 --> 03:10.358
but I'm desperate to fix it.

03:12.026 --> 03:14.362
Have you considered why you strayed?

03:16.114 --> 03:18.283
How's your husband
to trust it won't happen again?

03:18.366 --> 03:20.910
- Because it won't.
- How can he trust that?

03:22.287 --> 03:24.414
- Why should he?
- Thank you.

03:25.540 --> 03:28.668
We'll turn to your betrayal in a minute.

03:28.751 --> 03:30.003
My betrayal?

03:30.086 --> 03:34.424
Adultery is one form of infidelity.
Indifference is another.

03:34.507 --> 03:38.761
You describe yourself as a go-along,
get-along, don't-make-waves kind of guy.

03:38.845 --> 03:43.308
That makes you either wonderfully
accommodating or profoundly disengaged.

03:44.559 --> 03:47.896
Could it be Madeline was just trying
to get your attention?

03:47.979 --> 03:51.149
She has always had my attention.

03:52.901 --> 03:57.322
Devotion on my end
has not been a problem.

04:01.242 --> 04:04.078
Why were you unfaithful?

04:04.162 --> 04:06.331
- I don't know.
- If you were to guess?

04:07.916 --> 04:09.292
Should I guess?

04:11.085 --> 04:12.503
You don't believe in you.

04:12.587 --> 04:14.505
How can you trust the relational equation

04:14.589 --> 04:16.632
when you have no faith
in the sum part of you?

04:16.716 --> 04:20.011
- Math's not my strong suit, so...
- Because you didn't go to college?

04:20.094 --> 04:21.012
I'm sorry?

04:21.095 --> 04:24.766
You spoke earlier of your daughter
not wanting to go to college.

04:24.849 --> 04:27.060
Does that have something to do
with her perception...?

04:27.143 --> 04:29.562
I don't see where
that is relevant.

04:29.646 --> 04:30.897
Did you go to college?

04:32.774 --> 04:36.361
Again, I don't see the connection
between what's going on...

04:36.444 --> 04:40.323
Abigail will be nothing without college
perhaps because you are?

04:45.078 --> 04:46.996
Have you been feeding her this?

04:47.080 --> 04:49.457
Why did your first husband leave you?

04:50.416 --> 04:51.918
Because he's an asshole.

04:55.254 --> 04:57.799
Tell me about your parents.
What was their marriage like?

04:59.008 --> 05:00.008
- Fine.
- Fine?

05:00.051 --> 05:03.638
- Married for 40 years.
- Forty years. You talk to them much?

05:15.066 --> 05:17.402
<i>You have to be able
to hold your breath, baby.</i>

05:17.485 --> 05:19.278
<i>But I don't like it.</i>

05:21.114 --> 05:22.699
<i>You know what?</i>

05:22.782 --> 05:25.076
<i>I hate getting my head wet too,</i>

05:25.159 --> 05:27.245
we have to be able to hold our breath
underwater

05:27.328 --> 05:29.956
so if something ever happens,
we don't drown, baby.

05:33.543 --> 05:35.420
I don't want to.

05:41.592 --> 05:45.221
Maybe when I was 3, 4,
I walked into my parent's bedroom,

05:45.304 --> 05:50.351
and my dad was having sex with a woman
that wasn't my mom.

05:50.435 --> 05:54.856
And they were making all kinds of noises,
and then I got scared.

05:54.939 --> 05:56.315
And what happened?

05:57.692 --> 05:59.110
He pulled me out.

05:59.193 --> 06:00.570
- Oh.
- Um...

06:01.571 --> 06:04.282
And closed the door, and he said:

06:04.365 --> 06:07.910
"There are things
your mother doesn't ever need to know."

06:07.994 --> 06:10.580
- And you've never talked about it?
- No.

06:13.624 --> 06:18.755
I guess that maybe that's why
I was so devastated when Nathan left me.

06:20.048 --> 06:23.176
Because it confirmed
my biggest fear about marriage.

06:25.261 --> 06:26.971
It's not to be trusted.

06:28.181 --> 06:29.891
I wouldn't give up on Ed.

06:32.393 --> 06:33.478
All right?

06:33.561 --> 06:35.521
I really fucked up.

06:35.605 --> 06:38.149
He's not gonna leave you. Not Ed.

06:41.778 --> 06:43.029
How are you doing?

06:44.238 --> 06:47.075
Have you had
any more early morning joyrides?

06:49.285 --> 06:50.161
Funny.

06:50.244 --> 06:54.248
No, I'm not being funny.
It actually really scared me.

06:54.332 --> 06:56.459
What did Madam Shrink have to say
about that?

06:56.542 --> 06:59.253
She thinks it's somehow tied to me...

07:01.881 --> 07:04.050
not being sufficiently over Perry.

07:06.094 --> 07:07.970
Life just feels colorless now.

07:08.054 --> 07:10.473
It just feels flat and dull.

07:13.142 --> 07:17.688
As dead as he is,
sometimes I think maybe I'm deader.

07:19.065 --> 07:20.441
I was a better mother.

07:20.525 --> 07:23.194
- No. Honey...
- I was a better mother with him. I was.

07:23.277 --> 07:25.655
- No. Don't say that.
- Yes. I was.

07:28.074 --> 07:30.034
I need to find joy for them.

07:31.953 --> 07:33.830
And he helps me with that.

07:46.300 --> 07:47.552
Jane.

07:47.635 --> 07:49.554
- Yeah?
- I'm Mary Louise Wright.

07:49.637 --> 07:50.930
Uh, we may have met.

07:51.013 --> 07:53.641
- I'm Max and Josh's grandmother.
- Yeah, hi.

07:53.724 --> 07:57.478
I'm sorry to trouble you
here at work, but, um...

07:57.562 --> 08:02.650
Celeste has shared with me
some interesting news.

08:02.733 --> 08:05.862
How would you feel
about submitting to a paternity test?

08:06.946 --> 08:09.740
I mean, submitting Ziggy
to a paternity test.

08:12.368 --> 08:14.912
Uh, yeah,
I don't need to take a paternity test.

08:14.996 --> 08:16.998
I know exactly who my son's father is.

08:17.081 --> 08:19.834
- Hmm. Even so...
- I'm not asking you for anything.

08:19.917 --> 08:21.711
No, I realize that.

08:21.794 --> 08:23.462
I suppose I'm asking.

08:24.672 --> 08:25.548
For what?

08:25.631 --> 08:30.428
Well, I'm presented with the idea
that my son was both an adulterer and a...

08:30.511 --> 08:31.596
And a rapist.

08:31.679 --> 08:35.015
And I am desperate to squash that idea.

08:35.099 --> 08:39.937
Mm. Well, I can tell you
that he's the only man I'd been with.

08:40.020 --> 08:41.272
That you recall.

08:41.355 --> 08:42.732
Excuse me?

08:42.815 --> 08:44.483
Things happen these days.

08:44.567 --> 08:47.778
Men put drugs in pretty girls' drinks,
things happen.

08:47.862 --> 08:49.906
People don't remember sometimes.

08:49.989 --> 08:50.989
I remember.

08:51.949 --> 08:52.992
Perfectly.

08:54.202 --> 08:56.370
Far more vividly than I care to.

08:58.039 --> 08:59.999
- Just a simple blood test.
- No.

09:05.922 --> 09:11.969
<i>What a tangled web we weave
when first we practice to deceive.</i>

09:12.053 --> 09:14.931
But Charlotte didn't say that.
She said, "Some Pig."

09:15.014 --> 09:16.974
She didn't say anything
about a tangled web.

09:17.058 --> 09:18.893
She certainly spun one.

09:18.976 --> 09:21.270
I mean, she made Wilbur out
to be an outlier

09:21.354 --> 09:24.357
when in truth, he was kind of ordinary.

09:24.440 --> 09:25.608
So, Ziggy...

09:27.151 --> 09:28.778
does that make Charlotte a liar?

09:32.281 --> 09:33.950
It makes her a grownup.

09:34.033 --> 09:37.078
Lying to protect someone she loves,
that's what grownups do.

09:37.161 --> 09:40.164
I think
she was probably just rebranding Wilbur.

09:40.248 --> 09:41.749
Rebranding?

09:41.832 --> 09:42.917
I see.

09:43.000 --> 09:46.837
- Well, you all wanna know what I think?
- Uh-huh.

09:46.921 --> 09:51.175
I think Charlotte didn't want Wilbur
to get eaten.

09:51.259 --> 09:55.763
I don't think she wanted any pigs
to be eaten, and we all know why, don't we?

09:55.846 --> 09:58.266
Sustainability.

09:58.349 --> 10:00.309
Exactly. Exactly.

10:00.393 --> 10:04.188
How many gallons of water does it take
to make a single pound of sausage?

10:04.272 --> 10:06.274
A thousand.

10:06.357 --> 10:09.151
A thousand gallons. And how many
showers does that add up to?

10:09.235 --> 10:10.778
Over 50.

10:11.320 --> 10:13.155
Over 50 showers.

10:13.239 --> 10:16.867
So imagine, you would have
to take a shower every single day

10:16.951 --> 10:19.328
for almost two months to...

10:23.708 --> 10:24.917
ETA about 10 minutes.

10:25.001 --> 10:28.170
Amabella, your mother's gonna meet
you at the hospital, okay, sweetie?

10:28.254 --> 10:29.463
I wanna go with her.

10:29.547 --> 10:31.924
We've got you covered.
Let me get her backpack.

10:32.008 --> 10:34.093
What the fu... What happened?

10:34.176 --> 10:39.140
- Mrs. Klein.
- What... I'm Amabella's mom. Renata Klein.

10:39.223 --> 10:42.435
- What did she do? What's...?
- Mrs. Klein. I'm Dr. Feldman.

10:42.518 --> 10:44.770
Your daughter was brought in
with an anxiety attack.

10:44.854 --> 10:45.854
Anxiety attack?

10:45.896 --> 10:49.275
We've given her a mild sedative,
she's resting, she's not in any danger.

10:49.358 --> 10:51.944
She was in a little bit of a shock
when she first came in.

10:52.028 --> 10:53.654
- What?
- She's fine. She's resting.

10:53.738 --> 10:55.489
- Okay.
- Yeah. Right this way.

10:55.573 --> 10:56.699
What did you do?

11:00.745 --> 11:05.541
Did somebody hurt you
or say something or...?

11:05.624 --> 11:08.002
No. I'm okay, Mom.

11:08.085 --> 11:09.420
Sweetheart.

11:09.503 --> 11:13.007
You were discovered in a closet
practically unconscious.

11:13.090 --> 11:16.052
- Was she checked for bite marks?
- Honey, come on.

11:16.135 --> 11:18.763
She was bitten last year, right?
So...

11:18.846 --> 11:21.265
Maybe somebody's bullying you again or...

11:21.349 --> 11:23.059
- No.
- Hey, baby,

11:23.142 --> 11:24.310
you okay there, my girl?

11:24.393 --> 11:28.564
Don't talk to her. I got this, okay?
I think you've done enough, don't you?

11:28.647 --> 11:31.609
You...
What the hell are you talking about?

11:31.692 --> 11:35.029
Gordon, she's obviously
under immense stress.

11:35.112 --> 11:37.281
You think, Renata?

11:37.365 --> 11:39.533
- Team. Team.
- Yes.

11:39.617 --> 11:43.037
Hello, doctor. I would like my daughter
transferred to Stanford, please.

11:44.163 --> 11:48.167
- Because?
- Because it's Stanford. I mean, please.

11:48.250 --> 11:50.836
Well, she's being released.
She's cleared for discharge.

11:50.920 --> 11:52.713
- Oh, well, look at that.
- There we go.

11:52.797 --> 11:55.383
- Hey.
- Counseling is certainly indicated.

11:56.842 --> 11:59.095
Perhaps for the entire family.

11:59.178 --> 12:02.306
You don't know anything about my family.
Okay?

12:02.390 --> 12:05.726
I know your own stress,
not helping the situation.

12:05.810 --> 12:08.312
"Your own stress..."

12:08.396 --> 12:09.396
Please.

12:09.438 --> 12:12.733
Honey, isn't that great?
We're gonna go home.

12:12.817 --> 12:14.318
- You're going home.
- Don't talk.

12:17.780 --> 12:19.407
Will you ever forgive me?

12:19.490 --> 12:22.159
Yes, of course, honey. It's not your fault.

12:22.243 --> 12:23.953
I blurted it out.

12:24.036 --> 12:26.080
The blurting is not the problem.

12:26.163 --> 12:28.040
My doing it is the problem.

12:29.458 --> 12:32.670
- You're in therapy, so that's good. Right?
- Yeah.

12:33.838 --> 12:38.217
I mean, the doctor's pretty much a crock.
She...

12:38.300 --> 12:41.887
She thinks I feel like an empty sack
because I didn't graduate from college,

12:41.971 --> 12:44.473
and that's why I'm obsessed
with your going.

12:44.557 --> 12:47.977
But that is not entirely true.

12:48.060 --> 12:51.605
Mom... I mean,
when we would watch <i>The Wizard of Oz,</i>

12:51.689 --> 12:55.943
you would turn into a puddle
every time The Scarecrow got his diploma.

12:58.821 --> 13:03.617
Well, I'm glad you're back home.
Otherwise, I might be totally alone.

13:05.119 --> 13:06.662
He's not gonna leave you.

13:11.041 --> 13:13.210
Hello.

13:13.294 --> 13:14.336
Oh.

13:14.420 --> 13:18.174
We had such wonderful fun together.

13:18.257 --> 13:20.384
- Did you, honey?
- Yeah.

13:20.468 --> 13:23.095
- Can Dr. Peep have a sleepover?
- Oh.

13:23.179 --> 13:28.642
Oh, sweetheart, I would love that,
but I need to get back to my sheep.

13:28.726 --> 13:31.187
I'm afraid they'd miss me.

13:31.270 --> 13:33.689
Could I talk to your parents
for a second in private?

13:33.772 --> 13:35.357
Maybe you wanna go play outside?

13:35.441 --> 13:37.818
- Look at the sunset.
- I promise to come see you again.

13:37.902 --> 13:40.112
I'll bring tea and crumpets.

13:40.196 --> 13:41.196
Cool.

13:42.156 --> 13:43.574
I'll be right out.

13:43.657 --> 13:47.745
We arranged all her stuffies
into a petting zoo. It was wonderful.

13:53.667 --> 13:55.294
Nobody's bullying her.

13:55.377 --> 13:57.713
- She's worried about the end of the planet.
- What?

13:57.796 --> 14:00.049
Her class is evidently talking
about climate change,

14:00.132 --> 14:02.510
she's gotten the message
that we're doomed.

14:02.593 --> 14:03.886
- For fuck's sake.
- Oh, my God.

14:03.969 --> 14:07.473
- You gotta be kidding me.
- She's also worried about you going to jail.

14:07.556 --> 14:08.766
Well, hello.

14:08.849 --> 14:10.976
And she's worried about you.

14:11.060 --> 14:12.228
Me?

14:12.311 --> 14:15.606
She thinks something is going on with you
and has been for a long time.

14:16.690 --> 14:21.570
So there's you, you,
mostly the end of the world.

14:22.988 --> 14:26.534
- Do you know if it's wild or farmed?
- I believe it's farmed.

14:26.617 --> 14:29.036
- Land-based or net-pen?
- Sorry?

14:29.119 --> 14:32.456
Were they raised on land-based facilities
or in net-pens in the ocean?

14:32.540 --> 14:36.710
Well, um, it's a fish,
so I'm guessing the ocean.

14:36.794 --> 14:38.087
Could you check?

14:38.963 --> 14:40.923
- Sure.
- Thanks.

14:42.591 --> 14:44.301
- Sorry.
- It's okay.

14:44.385 --> 14:46.554
You have to be careful
with some of the farm shit.

14:46.637 --> 14:48.556
So you just eat wild?

14:48.639 --> 14:51.225
Yeah, yeah, mostly.
There's problems there too.

14:51.308 --> 14:53.936
Some wild fish have tested positive
for microplastics.

14:54.019 --> 14:56.522
Some wild salmon have tested positive
for antidepressants.

14:58.023 --> 14:59.942
People have to ask
where the fish come from,

15:00.025 --> 15:02.736
what they ate, how they lived,
even how they died.

15:02.820 --> 15:07.533
If they're processed post-rigor,
the bacteria can leech right into the flesh.

15:10.619 --> 15:13.956
- Sorry.
- No, you don't have to apologize.

15:14.039 --> 15:17.793
I used to work at Santa Monica Seafood,
so I was really into all this shit.

15:17.876 --> 15:20.421
It's great. And you're teaching me a lot.

15:20.504 --> 15:23.090
- I'm trying to come off intelligent.
- It's working.

15:29.013 --> 15:32.725
I'm so sorry.
I'm so sorry to be such a nuisance.

15:32.808 --> 15:34.310
But I was just...

15:34.393 --> 15:38.147
I was just wondering if there are any
new developments in the case.

15:39.523 --> 15:43.277
We told you we would call if there were.

15:43.360 --> 15:44.445
Yes.

15:44.528 --> 15:46.155
Mm-hm.

15:46.238 --> 15:50.743
I have personally worked very hard
to be mindful of your unspeakable pain.

15:50.826 --> 15:52.453
I know you care.

15:52.536 --> 15:55.414
I, perhaps, do seek out those who do.

15:55.497 --> 15:59.460
I know you are not allowed
to say anything about the case,

15:59.543 --> 16:02.755
or what you believe, but...

16:06.759 --> 16:07.801
A mother need...

16:09.928 --> 16:11.680
A mother needs to know.

16:14.850 --> 16:18.187
You don't believe my son just slipped.

16:21.774 --> 16:22.774
Do you?

16:25.194 --> 16:29.281
You don't think it's healthy
to cling to the good memories?

16:29.365 --> 16:31.784
It can be. I don't think so here.

16:31.867 --> 16:34.745
But there are so many positives.

16:34.828 --> 16:38.082
So many. The way he loved me,
the way he loved the boys.

16:38.165 --> 16:39.833
The boys loved him. I...

16:41.251 --> 16:45.255
I shouldn't erase all of that
simply because you feel that...

16:45.339 --> 16:47.675
He almost killed you.

16:47.758 --> 16:49.176
He didn't almost kill me.

16:49.259 --> 16:51.762
He nearly smothered you with a cushion.

16:51.845 --> 16:56.266
If one of his kicks had landed on your head,
you might very well be dead.

17:00.270 --> 17:04.273
I work with,
and treat, quite a few veterans.

17:04.358 --> 17:06.109
Many wanna return to combat.

17:06.193 --> 17:08.779
They can't handle the mundane.
Normal life is dull.

17:11.406 --> 17:13.617
You miss the war, Celeste.

17:15.577 --> 17:19.039
I miss what was good.
I don't miss what was bad.

17:19.123 --> 17:23.752
And keeping him in my heart, the good...
The good part of him, that works for me.

17:23.836 --> 17:27.589
It works for the boys.
It works for my family. That works.

17:29.508 --> 17:32.678
How did you get that bruise
on your arm?

17:32.761 --> 17:35.556
- I broke up a fight between the boys.
- Mm-hm.

17:35.639 --> 17:38.100
Last week.
I probably got whacked or something.

17:39.727 --> 17:41.895
Do you self-inflict your bruises?

17:41.979 --> 17:43.939
- What?
- It's not uncommon.

17:44.022 --> 17:49.903
Victims of abuse, sometimes they feel
some attachment to their wounds.

17:51.739 --> 17:53.741
Perhaps they remind you of him.

17:53.824 --> 17:57.327
I do not self-inflict any wounds.

17:58.579 --> 18:02.040
And your other patients
do not inform on me. I'm not a statistic.

18:03.083 --> 18:05.544
Are you an addict, Celeste?

18:05.627 --> 18:07.087
Is Perry your drug?

18:11.091 --> 18:15.345
I think it's really neat
how passionate you are about things.

18:15.429 --> 18:18.390
Thank you.
Are you passionate about things?

18:19.224 --> 18:22.019
Um, yeah, of course, I am. You know, I...

18:22.102 --> 18:25.189
I used to paint a lot.
I was really into art.

18:26.523 --> 18:31.695
Now I'm mostly passionate
about my son.

18:31.779 --> 18:32.654
I have a kid.

18:32.738 --> 18:38.035
I probably should've told you that earlier,
but it's kind of a weird thing to bring up.

18:39.661 --> 18:42.623
He's great. His name is Ziggy.
He's in second grade.

18:42.706 --> 18:43.832
